    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-15T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-15T08:00:00-05:00" n="362"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d362">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/3821: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-15T16:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 15, 1940—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 15—3:07 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>681. I have just been informed by the Associated Press correspondent that an
                    official communiqué was issued a few minutes ago by the Soviet Government
                    stating that an ultimatum addressed by it to the Lithuanian Government had been
                    accepted by the latter this morning at 9 o’clock, one hour before its time limit
                    expired.</p>
                <p>The communiqué which is not yet available to the Embassy is somewhat lengthy. I
                    understand that its principal points are that the former Lithuanian Minister of
                        Interior<note n="26" xml:id="d362fn26">K. Skucas, removed from his office on
                        June 13, 1940.</note> and head of the Political Police Department<note
                        n="27" xml:id="d362fn27">A. Povilaitis, Director of the Department of State
                        Security since 1932, removed from his office on June 13, 1940.</note> must
                    be brought to trial in connection with the Soviet protest, (Embassy’s telegram
                    601, May 29, 12 midnight) that the number of Soviet troops in Lithuania must be
                    increased and that the Lithuanian Government must be reorganized.</p>
                <p>Repeated [to] Kaunas and Riga.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thurston</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
